WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Hi, my name is Andrew Bray. I'm an Associate Teaching Professor at UC Berkeley in Statistics.

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:16.040
I'd like to tell you my top three reasons why you should take the Advanced Quarto with

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:22.080
R and RStudio workshop at PositConf this summer. Reason number one, projects in person. One

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:27.080
of the real strengths of Quarto and one of the focuses of this advanced workshop is on

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:32.360
Quarto projects. These are complex works like websites and books that allow you to

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:37.560
unite many different documents into a single published work. This can be challenging to

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:41.880
learn because instead of just looking at a single file, you're looking at many documents

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:47.439
that exist in a directory that has a particular structure. So for this workshop, we'll be

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:54.060
preparing ahead of time several project directories that will help guide exercises, each one focusing

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:59.220
on a different aspect of project functionality. So a big part of this workshop will just

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:05.540
be looking at the structure of these directories together in person. And this is really a terrific

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:12.860
environment to learn how these things work. Reason number two, programming plus authoring.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:16.620
If you're coming to PositConf, I know you like programming. If you're interested in

00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:21.500
Quarto, I also know you like authoring and publishing documents. In this workshop, we'll

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:25.900
look at some of the advanced features of Quarto where programming and authoring start

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:32.339
to merge. We'll look at how to pass variables through documents and how to implement listings.

00:01:32.339 --> 00:01:37.739
We'll also see how to do conditional formatting and how to set up project profiles. We'll

00:01:37.739 --> 00:01:42.739
learn how Quarto allows you to, in essence, apply programming principles to the authoring

00:01:42.739 --> 00:01:49.059
of your documents. That's a powerful paradigm. Reason number three, ask the experts. Quarto

00:01:49.059 --> 00:01:53.220
has grown leaps and bounds over the last two years, and there are more exciting changes

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:59.180
that are in the works. We'll be visited in this workshop by the project's primary developers.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:03.500
This will give you a chance to ask them some questions and hear about what's happening

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:08.220
at the cutting edge of Quarto. So if you're ready to expand what you can do with this

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:12.460
powerful new tool, please join us at the workshop in Chicago. We hope to see you there.

